english:
  title: Preface to a Poem on the Lotus Pavilion at Suwon
  author: Kwon Je
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring of the Year of the Horse, several of us—Governor Zhao Kekuan, Court Official Kwon Keho, and Governor Kim Dun of Changhung—having failed the civil service examination at the Ministry of Rites, journeyed south and arrived at this place. Ascending the pavilion, I marveled at its beauty and, wishing to capture its charm in words, declared: "Should there come a day when fine rain falls in mist, snow swirls in flurries, the moon shines clear through the eaves, and lotus fragrance fills our seats—then, gazing upon the land below with two or three companions, composing verses upon this pavilion, would surely repay us for this journey."

    My friends laughed heartily, saying, "What nonsense! If rain falls thick, snow cannot swirl. If rain and snow mingle, the moon cannot shine. How could lotus fragrance rise from winter snow?" I had no answer to give.

    In time, all these friends passed the higher examination and rose to prominence, serving in both capital and provinces. I too, lacking talent, followed in their wake. Whenever we met and spoke, we returned to this memory and laughed together.

    This spring, I received imperial favor and was appointed Provincial Inspector. Governor Zhao came to see me off. Raising his cup, he said, "The winter lotus of Suwon—at last we may behold it!" We smiled at the irony. Within months, Zhao was appointed to govern this very province.

    Three days after his arrival, I came on an official tour. We sat upon the pavilion, and as he joined me, the lotus flowers burst into bloom. Our eyes met across the blossoms; we laughed without words.

    Alas! When we once bore the sorrow of examination failure, wandering with only a horse and a single servant, worn by travel and hardship—who could have imagined that Heaven would raise us both to such stations? That Zhao would wear the crimson banner and black parasol of a governor, and I would hold the authority of an Inspector? Was it not Heaven and the spirits, moved by pity for our youthful struggles, that guided my careless words into prophecy? That very impossibility made it a jest we could never forget.

    How could such unreasonable words prove so true? This must be recorded. Therefore I write this poem and place it here.

    Moreover, Zhao's honored father governed this province before him. That father and son should serve this place in succession within a dozen years—this too is rare in this world, and worthy of record.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Year of the Horse' (甲午年) refers to 1474 in the Korean calendar during the Joseon Dynasty.
    - The 'civil service examination at the Ministry of Rites' (禮曹) was the highest level of the Korean civil service examination system.
    - The 'higher examination' (大科) was the most prestigious stage of the civil service system.
    - The 'red banner and black parasol' (朱幡皁蓋) were official insignia indicating a governor's rank and authority.
